{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"928ae2c8-8e1d-483f-ac09-5d61a40ac6e5","content":"The directory appears empty, so I'll answer from knowledge:\n\nTo switch from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform with MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0, you just need to **remove** (or set to `false`) the `<UseVSTest>` property:\n\n```xml\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n    <!-- Remove or set to false: -->\n    <!-- <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest> -->\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n1. **MSTest.Sdk 3.4+** defaults to Microsoft.Testing.Platform when `UseVSTest` is not set. Simply removing that property opts you in.\n\n2. **CLI change** — run tests with:\n   ```\n   dotnet test\n   ```\n   (still works, but now uses the new platform runner under the hood)\n\n   Or run the test executable directly:\n   ```\n   dotnet run --project YourTests.csproj\n   ```\n\n3. **If you use `dotnet test`** and need VSTest compatibility bridging (e.g., for CI `.trx` output), add:\n   ```xml\n   <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n   ```\n   The SDK already sets this by default when `UseVSTest` is absent.\n\n4. **Review any VSTest-specific `.runsettings`** — some settings (like data collectors) may need adjustment for the new platform.\n\nThat's it — the MSTest.Sdk handles the rest (test runner entry point, platform packages, etc.) automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0bfed81b-5adb-4ec9-aaab-049226464182","outputTokens":404,"requestId":"E83F:1F9B94:26284B5:28A13FC:6A0493B3"},"id":"bca1d660-e401-4085-8a82-d909d6812b68","timestamp":"2026-05-13T15:07:47.647Z","parentId":"38e58a6e-5b83-492c-9d86-c055eed90834"}
